FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, OVINE - CYPRUS (11): POSITIVE SEROLOGY, REQUEST
FOR INFORMATION
***************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Thu 15 Nov 2007
Source: The Cyprus Mail [edited]
<http://www.cyprus-mail.com/news/main.php?id=35942&cat_id=1>


If you take a drive through the streets of Dromolaxia, a once
anonymous village near Larnaca, you'll still get a sense of the slow
rhythm of life, but dig a little deeper and you'll find a community
in mourning.

Before 1974, Dromolaxia was a mixed village of Greek and Turkish
Cypriots. After the war, much of the land was expropriated and used
for livestock farming. The farms are all around the village and very
much a part of daily life and commerce.

Since the outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD], the village has
found itself at the heart of a 3-km (2 mi) exclusion zone, painting a
gloomy picture for its residents while instilling a sense of pending
doom for all the farmers in the area.

Veterinary Service officials dressed from head to toe in all-white
are everywhere as if on the set of a futuristic disaster movie. They
move around farms in white cars, spraying, decontaminating, setting
up check-points, testing animals, and when the order comes in,
culling and burying them.

The dirty business of mass killing has not gone unnoticed in the
coffee shops of Dromolaxia. One old man sipping coffee told the
Cyprus Mail that since the culling started, there was an unavoidable
sense of morbidity in the air.

"It's very hard to see the animals go. The farmers leave when they do
it. It's just a quick injection and then they drop. There's no
kicking or fussing, nothing. The farmers can't bear to watch. How can
you kill 2000 animals for one case of FMD? It's very sad," said
George Karajas, an 80-year-old refugee from Famagusta.

"It's much harder for the small farmers. They suffer more because
they look after their sheep day and night. Rain or snow, they are
there for them when they are pregnant, help them to give birth, milk
their young. For them it is very hard, they can't look," he added.
And of course, where there is a coffee shop, there are rumours.

"We hear whispers, rumours that they'll sell the farm land and others
will come and build a polyclinic there instead. Land prices have shot
up in this little village," said Karajas.

One farmer was having his animals tested by 2 men in white carrying
test tubes. He looked flustered and disturbed. "Look, I can't speak
now. They want to take more tests. I'm trying to finish with this
business for once and for all," he said, with the permanent frown
above his eyes revealing a month's worth of stress. Behind him,
dozens of sheep moved agitatedly around the 2 costumed Vet Service
officials, sounding as stressed as their owner. Asked if they were
slated for culling, he replied: "That's how it looks."

His neighbour was more optimistic: "I've been given the all clear but
they don't want to give me a certificate saying so. I don't know what
is going on. Is it possible FMD is really here? I mean look at these
animals, if they had fever, would they still be eating?"

The 2nd farmer felt the government was putting the EU before its own
people. "It's Europe first, Europe first. But no one knows what to do
here. If you go to the Vet Service and ask for vaccinations, they
say, go to the private sector. But when we say let us bring in
private experts to check for FMD, they say 'No'," said the goat
farmer. "And if anyone did buy faulty vaccinations from the north, no
one will admit it," he added.

[Subscribers's attention is drawn to the sentence above. The
possibility that vaccination has taken place in the past within
Cyprus territory(ies), or that vaccinated animals found their way
into local flocks, deserves thorough investigation. Its outcome may
be significant in explaining the detection of several seropositive
adult sheep within a population of susceptible, predominantly
seronegative population of sheep, goats, cattle, and pigs. See item 2
for the total number of tested animals. - Mod.AS]

"There's just no way of reaching a safe conclusion with all this. It
was the authorities that brought scrapie to the island from Germany.
We had no such thing in Cyprus." [Cyprus has a very high incidence of
scrapie, initially recorded and reported during the late 70s/early
80s of the previous century. Recently, the EU required the culling of
more than 110 000 sheep and goats because of scrapie. This
requirement has been contested by Cypriot farmers; the issue is
pending. - Mod.AS]

The farmer, who did not wish to be named, said the farm had been in
his family for over 80 years. Since the outbreak, fear, confusion,
and sadness hung above the farms like a dark cloud, he noted.

The Cyprus Mail tried to get to the Kyriacou farm, the site of mass
culling yesterday [15 Nov 2007] but was stopped by a checkpoint set
up by the Veterinary Service. A quick chat with a local in the coffee
shop revealed another way to the farm. Sure enough, the Vet officials
were more lenient there, allowing this reporter to pass without
question.

Once inside, an odd picture was painted of everyday routine with a
backdrop of abject abnormality. White-clad officials roamed around
hundreds of dead sheep, lying on the ground while some helpers passed
around drinks and water in a plastic bag. Dozens of sheep were loaded
by Vet Service employees onto a digger, which threw them onto a truck
to be dumped later in mass graves nearby.

The Vet Service follows strict procedures when working within the
zone. All workers go back to base after a day's work and burn their
white borrowed clothes. All cars get sprayed on the way out. And yet,
farmers in civilian clothing could go in and out of the farm without
obstruction. Even the Cyprus Mail slipped in, revealing a lax
attitude to the sealing of the exclusion zone.

As the camera snapped away, one of the workers caught wind of my
presence. "Oi! What the hell is that journalist doing there?"

One farmer observing the mass culling warned me to leave immediately
before they got ratty.

On the way out, I owned up to my intrusion, got my shoes and car
sprayed, leaving behind a chilling scene of work, routine and 1900
animals, dead.

[Byline: Stefanos Evripidou]

