******
[2]
Date: Thu 15 Nov 2007
Source: The Cyprus Mail [edited]
<http://www.cyprus-mail.com/news/main.php?id=35932&cat_id=1>


Yesterday [14 Nov 2007] 2 more farms in Dromolaxia felt the backlash
of recent FMD outbreak, with around 2000 animals slated for slaughter.

The Veterinary Services yesterday started culling animals from one of
the biggest farms in Cyprus, owned by Kyriacos Kyriacou, estimated to
hold around 1900 sheep, cows, and goats.

Today [15 Nov 2007] they will also be visiting a neighbouring farm to
cull all 80 farm animals there. Officials from the Services visited
the 2 farms early yesterday morning and informed the owners of the
decision.

The announcement naturally provoked reactions and it took 2 hours of
reasoning and the arrival of a strong police force for the farmers to
finally give in.

Kyriacou wanted to see the results of the European Lab tests before
allowing the veterinary services into his farm. Mayhem ensued as
other farmers in the area arrived to offer their support and it was
then that men from the Rapid Reaction Unit (MMAD) arrived to make
sure things didn't get out of hand.

Two hours later and after receiving the certificate from the EU lab,
which showed that at least one sheep from Kyriacou's flock had FMD,
he allowed the culling to begin, but not before reminding the
government of vast losses his sector had suffered.

["Had FMD," most probably, means that the animal was found positive,
at Pirbright -- the EU lab -- by the seroneutralisation test. -
Mod.AS]

The cull will continue today [15 Nov 2007] due to the large number of
animals that need to be slaughtered and it will expand to the
neighbouring farm that belongs to Costas Papadopoulos, who has
already been informed that his 80 sheep will be slaughtered. It was
determined there too that one of his animals was suffering from the
FMD.

[It is not clear if the animal above was tested in Cyprus or at
Pirbright. If at Pirbright, the comment in the previous passage is
applicable. If in Cyprus, the NSP I-ELISA (enzyme-linked
immunosorbent assay) 3ABC test has been performed, detecting NSPs
(non structural proteins). -Mod.AS]

Agriculture minister Fotis Fotiou said the decision was made on
Tuesday night [13 Nov 2007] after a lengthy meeting with the vet
services.

However, he said so far there were no other indications for positive
samples of FMD apart from these 2 cases. He added that the services
would continue to check farms for the next few weeks until the
problem is wiped out.

The minister also explained under which circumstances entire flocks
were killed and when only the animals that are affected. He said in
the cases that the disease is confirmed, the EU instructions are
clear that the entire farm's animals should be killed. While if it is
just a positive indication, then only the suspicious animals are
killed.

[The statement above is in need of clarification. Does it mean that
positive NSP I-ELISA 3ABC tests will be regarded as "confirmed",
while negative such tests, combined with positive seroneutralisation,
will be regarded as "positive indication"? - Mod.AS]

Fotiou said animals tested outside the 10 km (6 mi) quarantine zone
had so far "thankfully tested negative" to the disease.

According to an announcement by the Veterinary Services yesterday [14
Nov 2007], tests are carried out on a continuous and daily basis and
4084 samples from 152 [holdings] have been tested so far.

[It would be helpful to obtain figures on the segmentation of the
figure above among the various species included. - Mod.AS]

Animals from 4 farms in the 3 km (2 mi) exclusion zone in Dromolaxia
have been slaughtered.

The tests are carried out by specialists from the EU, the UN special
department for FMD, and a number of Greek vets.

"The Veterinary Services are sending out a plea to everybody for
cooperation in this truly big effort and expressing their thanks to
the state services and organisations for their contribution to these
efforts."

[Byline: Jacqueline Theodoulou]

