******
[3]
Date: Fri 16 Nov 2007
Source: The Cyprus Mail [edited]
<http://www.cyprus-mail.com:80/news/>


The head of Veterinary Services, Charalambos Kakoyiannis, told state
radio yesterday [15 Nov 2007] that mass culling was the only option
for the 2 farms after all alternatives had been exhausted.

Brussels made it crystal clear that there was no choice than to
proceed with the immediate culling of livestock or risk serious
consequences for Cyprus, including spread of the disease and further
measures taken by the EU, said Kakoyiannis.

Despite taking hard measures against FMD, the authorities have yet to
isolate the virus or locate its origin, the veterinary head warned.
This could take anywhere from days to months, he added.

On a more positive note, 4700 samples from 180 farms have come up
clear of the disease, meaning no FMD has been found outside of the 3
km (2 mi) exclusion zone in Dromolaxia, said Kakoyiannis.

[Byline: Stefanos Evripidou]

